content.text:
The issue was that `delay(Duration)` was truncating the duration to milliseconds, effectively rounding down. This caused delays to be shorter than requested when the duration had fractional milliseconds (e.g., microseconds or nanoseconds).

I fixed this by modifying `Duration.toDelayMillis()` in `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/Delay.kt`. The new implementation rounds up to the next millisecond if there is any fractional part, ensuring that the delay is at least as long as the requested duration. I also added a check to prevent overflow when calculating nanoseconds for large durations.

I verified the fix by creating a reproduction test case that checks if the actual delay is at least the requested duration (minus a small tolerance for clock precision, but definitely not shorter by a full millisecond). The test passed with the fix. I also ran existing tests to ensure no regressions.

Modified `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/Delay.kt`:
```kotlin
internal fun Duration.toDelayMillis(): Long =
    if (this > Duration.ZERO) {
        val millis = inWholeMilliseconds
        if (millis < Long.MAX_VALUE / 1_000_000) {
            val millisInNanos = millis * 1_000_000
            if (millisInNanos < inWholeNanoseconds) millis + 1 else millis.coerceAtLeast(1)
        } else {
            millis.coerceAtLeast(1)
        }
    } else 0
```

